sections.content:
Event loops minimise per-task overhead and expose a familiar single-threaded mental model, but they conflate scheduling with I/O dispatch and can be starved by CPU-bound work. The dominant escape hatches are:

- explicit blocking pools (Node.js `Worker`, Tokio `spawn_blocking`);
- cooperative yielding at well-defined safe points;
- per-loop timer wheels and microtask queues to keep work from accumulating in any one tick.

Languages choosing an event-loop scheduler trade I/O efficiency and predictable single-threaded semantics for the burden of educating users about CPU-bound starvation and the boundary between sync and async work.
